        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Creating MCP Servers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An MCP server is a standalone process that exposes capabilities \u2014 tools, resources, and prompts \u2014 to any MCP-capable client using the JSON-RPC 2.0 protocol. You author the tool logic; the MCP SDK handles framing, dispatch, and transport. This section walks through creating a production-quality server from a blank file to a deployed service."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "MCP server development lifecycle: define tools, implement logic, choose transport, test and deploy \u2014 plus anatomy of tools/resources/prompts layers"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "An MCP server only needs two handlers to be useful: list_tools() returning schema definitions, and call_tool() executing them. Everything else \u2014 transport framing, JSON-RPC routing, error formatting \u2014 is handled by the SDK."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Project Setup"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Install the Python MCP SDK and start with a minimal project layout:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "pip install mcp httpx\nmkdir my-mcp-server && cd my-mcp-server\ntouch server.py"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "mcp"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " package ships both the server framework and the client library. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "httpx"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is included here for tools that call external HTTP APIs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A Minimal Working Server"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The smallest valid MCP server registers one tool and exposes it over stdio. Every part is explained below the code."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nimport mcp.server.stdio\nfrom mcp.server import Server\nfrom mcp.types import Tool, TextContent\n\n# 1. Create the server \u2014 the name is sent to clients during initialization\napp = Server(\"calculator\")\n\n# 2. Register the tool catalogue\n@app.list_tools()\nasync def list_tools() -> list[Tool]:\n    return [\n        Tool(\n            name=\"add\",\n            description=\"Add two integers together\",\n            inputSchema={\n                \"type\": \"object\",\n                \"properties\": {\n                    \"a\": {\"type\": \"integer\", \"description\": \"First operand\"},\n                    \"b\": {\"type\": \"integer\", \"description\": \"Second operand\"},\n                },\n                \"required\": [\"a\", \"b\"],\n            },\n        )\n    ]\n\n# 3. Implement tool execution\n@app.call_tool()\nasync def call_tool(name: str, arguments: dict) -> list[TextContent]:\n    if name == \"add\":\n        result = arguments[\"a\"] + arguments[\"b\"]\n        return [TextContent(type=\"text\", text=str(result))]\n    raise ValueError(f\"Unknown tool: {name}\")\n\n# 4. Start the server using stdio transport\nasync def main():\n    async with mcp.server.stdio.stdio_server() as (read_stream, write_stream):\n        await app.run(\n            read_stream,\n            write_stream,\n            app.create_initialization_options(),\n        )\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    asyncio.run(main())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
